'''George de Benneville''' ([[London]], 25 July 1703 – [[Pennsylvania]], 19 March 1793) was a physician and [[Christian Universalist]] preacher.<ref name=AMB>{{Cite AMB1920|wstitle=Benneville, George de}}</ref>

==Biography==
He was born in [[London]] in 1703 to aristocratic [[Huguenot]] French parents in the court of [[Anne, Queen of Great Britain|Queen Anne]]. While serving as a [[sailor]] during his adolescent years, de Benneville traveled around the world and began to question his religion and compare it to other [[major world religions|world religions]]. He shed his Huguenot religion, developed his own ideas about [[Christianity]], and became a [[preacher]] while still in his teens.

De Benneville had a mystical experience and later a [[near death experience]] which he described in ''The Life and Trance of Dr. George De Benneville''.  These experiences convinced him that Hell is for purification, not punishment, and that, ultimately, all will be united with God.  He believed that [[God]] is absolutely good and in his love would never condemn any human to eternal [[damnation]]. He also preached that each human being has a [[mind-body dualism|dualistic]] nature; the outer, flesh-and-blood person is subject to the evils of the world and may choose to do good or to do wrong, while the inner, spiritlike person is crafted by God and is perfect, immaculate, and holy, and cannot be damned. Therefore, all human beings experience [[salvation]].  

Religious authorities in several nations were disturbed by [[evangelism|evangelists]] such as de Benneville, and he was [[capital punishment|sentenced to death]] more than once. He preached and practiced medicine in France and Germany. After completing medical training in Europe, de Benneville immigrated to the [[thirteen colonies|American colonies]] during the mid-eighteenth century with others seeking [[religious toleration|religious tolerance]]. He settled in [[Pennsylvania]] and worked as a physician and [[apothecary]] in [[Oley Township, Berks County, Pennsylvania|Oley]], [[Berks County, Pennsylvania|Berks County]], using free time to continue his [[Universalism|Universalist]] preaching.

de Benneville socialized and traded [[herbalism|herbal preparations]] with [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] groups in the area. His beliefs stressed that all people everywhere are loved by God, and cultures, races, and sexes have no bearing on the worth of a human being. His beliefs stated clearly that the physical body is merely one part of a person.

George de Benneville died at home in Pennsylvania in 1793.

