{{Chinese name|[[Nie (surname)|Nie]]}}
'''Nie Yuanzi''' ({{zh|c=聂元梓|p=Niè Yuánzǐ}}; born 5 April 1921) is a Chinese academic who taught philosophy at [[Peking University]]. She is primarily known for writing a [[big-character poster]] criticising the university for being controlled by the [[bourgeoisie]], which has been credited with launching the [[Cultural Revolution]].{{sfnp|Honig|2003|p=149}}<ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/asia/article716278.ece Times Online]</ref>

==Background==
Nie joined the [[Communist Party of China]] in 1938 as a [[Middle school#China|middle school student]].{{sfnp|Walder|2006|p=1025}}

==Cultural Revolution==
[[File:Nie Yuanzi poster.jpg|thumb|right|This famous photo of Nie Yuanzi's poster helped spark the Cultural Revolution.]]
Nie's [[big-character poster]] was put up on 25 May 1966. In it, she criticised Song Shuo, deputy director of the Beijing Municipal University Bureau, Lu Ping, the [[President of Peking University]] and head of its Communist Party committee, and [[Peng Peiyun]], an official in the Beijing Municipal University Bureau. Although Nie's main criticism was the control of Peking University by the [[bourgeoisie]], the aim of the campaign was to legitimise the purge of the Beijing municipal party chief [[Peng Zhen]], by exposing his crime of supporting a bourgeoise [[reactionary]] education line. This was pushed by members of the radical clique surround [[Mao Zedong]], including [[Kang Sheng]] and Cao Yi'ou.{{sfnp|Dong|2010|p=31}} This inspired students at other universities to write posters, most of which expressed support for the "revolutionary action" of Nie Yuanzi.{{sfnp|Dong|2010|p=38}}

When she published the poster, Nie was one of [[Peking University]]'s top 30 officials on the Party committee. She was married to an official in the [[Central Commission for Discipline Inspection]] and, along with her husband, Nie often socialised with ministerial-level officials.{{sfnp|Walder|2006|p=1025}}

Nie initially supported the persecution of other academics, but later disagreed on the course the Cultural Revolution was taking and tried to quit her position in the [[Red Guards (China)|Red Guards]]. She controlled revolutionary activities at [[Peking University]], along with her colleagues, protected by her status as a celebrated rebel.{{sfnp|Dong|2010|p=46}}

Nie was made an alternate member of the [[9th Central Committee of the Communist Party of China]]. In December 1969, she was sent to labour at a farm owned by [[Peking University]] in Liyuzhou ({{zh|c=鲤鱼洲}}), [[Jiangxi]]. She returned to Beijing in 1970 to recuperate from illness.<ref name=renmin>{{cite web|editor=Zhang Aijing 张爱敬|title=蒯大富聂元梓……文革时五大学生"领袖"今安在|trans-title=Kuai Dafu, Nie Yuanzi... five university student 'leaders' of the Cultural Revolution still live|publisher=Renmin Wang|date=18 November 2003|accessdate=3 February 2017|url=http://www.people.com.cn/GB/wenhua/1088/2196430.html}}</ref>

==Post-revolution==
In 1971, Nie was subjected to examination and her movements were restricted. In 1973, she was sent to work in the [[Xinhua News Agency#History|Xinhua Printing House]], where she lived, ate and slept in the factory. She moved to a factory that made apparatuses for [[Peking University]] in 1975. On 19 April 1978, Nie was sent to [[Yanqing Prison]].<ref name=renmin/>

==Post-Mao==
Nie is critical of the post-Mao Chinese regime and has expressed a desire for greater freedom of opinion.{{sfnp|French|2006}}

In 2005, Nie's memoirs were published.<ref name=cnny>{{cite web|last1=Liu 刘|first1=Ruo 若|title=聂元梓文革后的半生点滴|trans-title=Nie Yuanzi's half-life after the Cultural Revolution|date=19 May 2016|url=http://cn.nytimes.com/china/20160519/cc19nie/|accessdate=3 February 2017|publisher=New York Times}}</ref>

In [[Ji Xianlin]]'s memoir Cowshed: Memories of the Chinese Cultural Revolution, Xianlin speaks of her capriciousness, cruelty and remarkable arrogance.

