{{China-academic-bio-stub}}

'''Piet Hein Hoebens''' (29 September 1948, [[Utrecht]] - 22 October 1984)<ref>Gerd H. Hövelmann, Hans Michels, [https://books.google.com/books?id=ZHgiDgAAQBAJ&dq=Legitimacy+of+Unbelief:+The+Collected+Papers+of+Piet+Hein+Hoebens&source=gbs_navlinks_s Legitimacy of Unbelief: The Collected Papers of Piet Hein Hoebens], LIT Verlag Münster, 2017</ref><ref>Hans Peter Duerr, [https://books.google.com/books?id=SdQLAAAAYAAJ&q=%22Hoebens%22+1948+Utrecht&dq=%22Hoebens%22+1948+Utrecht&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwju6emM35_SAhUU5GMKHQQpDVYQ6AEIITAB Authentizität und Betrug in der Ethnologie], Suhrkamp, 1987, p. 419</ref> was a Dutch [[journalist]], [[parapsychologist]] and [[Skepticism|skeptic]]. 

Hoebens is most well known for debunking the claims of [[psychic detective]]s.<ref>Stoke, Douglas M. (1997) ''The Nature of Mind''. McFarland. p. 51. {{ISBN|978-0786477548}}</ref> He worked as a Dutch journalist and investigated claims of [[paranormal]] phenomena. He was a staff member for the newspaper ''[[De Telegraaf]]'' for 13 years and a member of the [[Committee for Skeptical Inquiry]]. 

He was an associate of [[Marcello Truzzi]] and contributed to the ''[[Zetetic Scholar]]'' regarding the claims of psychics such as [[Peter Hurkos]] and [[Gerard Croiset]] which he found to be bogus.<ref>Neher, Andrew. (2011). ''Paranormal and Transcendental Experience: A Psychological Examination''. Dover Publications. p. 310. {{ISBN|0-486-26167-0}}</ref><ref>[[Robert Todd Carroll|Carroll, Robert Todd]]. (2003). ''The Skeptic's Dictionary: A Collection of Strange Beliefs, Amusing Deceptions, and Dangerous Delusions''. John Wiley & Sons. p. 311. {{ISBN|978-0-471-27242-7}}</ref>

Hoebens took his own life in October 1984.<ref>Gerd H. Hövelmann, [http://hetjohanborgmanfonds.nl/wp-content/uploads/2014/06/PHCP-Brochure-2014_small.pdf Piet Hein Hoebens (1948-1984)]</ref>

