{{Infobox governor |name = Udoakaha Jacob Esuene |image = |office1 = Governor of South-Eastern State |term_start1 = 28 May 1967 |term_end1 = July 1975 |predecessor1 = [[Chukwuemeka Odumegwu Ojukwu]] (Eastern Region) |successor1 = [[Paul Omu]] |birth_date = 1936 |birth_place = |death_date = 1993 |party = MPN (1978), UPN (1982), SDP (1990) }} Brigadier '''Udoakaha Jacob Esuene''' (1936 &ndash; 1993) was a [[Nigeria]]n air force officer who was Military Governor of [[South-Eastern State, Nigeria|South-Eastern State]] (later renamed [[Cross River State]]) between May 1967 and July 1975 during the military regime of General [[Yakubu Gowon]]. He was the first governor after the state was formed in May 1967 when [[Eastern Region, Nigeria|Eastern Region]] was split into [[East-Central State]], [[Rivers State]] and [[South-Eastern State, Nigeria|South-Eastern]] states.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldstatesmen.org/Nigeria_federal_states.htm |title=Nigerian States |publisher=WorldStatesmen |accessdate=2010-01-01}}</ref>
Esuene, who was of [[Ibibio people|Ibibio]] ethnicity, was a fighter pilot before being appointed governor of South-Eastern State.<ref name=helen>{{cite web |url=http://allafrica.com/stories/200912140759.html |title=Helen Esuene Emerging From the Shadow of a Famous Husband |author=Nseobong Okon-Ekong |date=12 December 2009 |work=ThisDay |accessdate=2010-02-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.omoigui.com/files/the_bakassi_story.pdf |title=The Bakassi Story |author=Nowa Omoigui |date=24 September 2004 |work=Omoigui.com - Blog of Nigerian Military History |accessdate=2010-02-27}}</ref> Esuene was dismissed by General [[Murtala Muhammed]] when he seized power in July 1975, was charged and found guilt of illegally enriching himself while in office, and was dismissed from the military.<ref>{{cite book |title=Oil, politics and violence: Nigeria's military coup culture (1966–1976) |author=[[Max Siollun]] |publisher=Algora Publishing |year=2009 |ISBN=0-87586-708-1 |page=186}}</ref> The dismissal was, however, reversed by the [[Armed Forces Ruling Council (Nigeria)|Armed Forces Ruling Council]] led by the then Military President; General Ibrahim Babaginda. General Esuene's rank and benefits were restored and backdated to 1975.{{Citation needed|date=July 2010}} In the run-up to the 1993 presidential election, he was a candidate for the presidential ticket of the [[Social Democratic Party (Nigeria)|Social Democratic Party]] (SDP).<ref name=helen/>
After his death, his wife [[Helen Esuene]] was appointed Minister of State for Health, and later Minister of Environment and Housing in the Cabinet of President Olusegun Obasanjo between 2005 and 2007.<ref name=helen/>
